<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Prepares To Debate `Controversial Issue' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliament Prepares To Debate `Controversial Issue' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2804220794 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1750 GMT 27 Apr 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2804220794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Walfredo Angulo] </F>
  [Text] Havana, 27 Apr (PL) -- The Cuban parliament is 
preparing to debate the controversial issue of cleaning up its 
internal finances without resorting to the classical mechanisms 
of neoliberalism, as the country faces the most difficult 
economic situation in 30 years. 
  Financial adjustments and shock policies have been ruled out 
by the authorities because the effects on the population would 
be incomparably worse, according to Carlos Lage Davila, 
secretary of the Council of Ministers Executive Committee. 
  Many parliamentarians have said the best technical solution 
must be politically feasible and consistent with the strategic 
goal of protecting the social accomplishments achieved over 
three decades. 
  These measures, these sources say, must have the support of 
the majority of the people, hence the great effort recently made 
to extend the debate to work centers and encourage millions of 
people to directly participate in this process, popularly called 
workers parliaments. 
  The issue was extensively debated by approximately 3 million 
workers, who attended more than 80,000 meetings held between 
January and March at their work centers to analyze the 
improvement of internal finances. 
  With a fiscal deficit of more that 4.2 billion pesos 
(equivalent to U.S. dollars at the official exchange rate) and 
excess money in circulation amounting to approximately 11 
billion, Cuban authorities are seeking formulas to correct 
Cuba's finances and economic feasibility and reduce the two 
indexes. 
  Parliament President Ricardo Alarcon said there is a 
consensus that no single measure will perform the miracle unless 
it is accompanied by an increase in production and economic 
efficiency. What is more, we are trying to earn greater profits 
in state-owned companies, 69 percent of which are currently 
losing money, Alarcon admitted. 
  Strengthening the national currency, encouraging work and 
production, and restoring the role of the salary are other goals 
the National Assembly could present in the special period of 
sessions to begin on 1 May. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

