<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coffee-Producing Association Ends Retention Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Coffee-Producing Association Ends Retention Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2804155994 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2214 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2804155994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] San Salvador, 27 Apr (ACAN-EFE) -- Member countries 
of the Association of Coffee-Producing Countries (APC) have 
decided to end today, Wednesday, the plan to retain coffee 
beans, because the bean has experienced an important recovery on 
the international market, official Salvadoran sources have 
reported. 
  Ruben Pineda, president of the Salvadoran Coffee Council, 
has 
told ACAN-EFE the coffee-exporting countries, headed by Brazil 
and Colombia, have decided to end the retention, because the 
pound of the bean has exceeded the minimum price of 80 cents on 
the world market. 
  "We received the notification at our offices this morning 
from the retention plan coordinating office, located in New 
York, stating there would be 0-percent retention as of today," 
Pineda has said. 
  The retention plan of the approximately 30-member APC 
countries started on 1 October 1993, negatively affecting 20 
percent of the coffee production in each country, but due to the 
success of the measure, producers decided to reduce retention to 
10 percent only four weeks ago. 
  Pineda has said the lifting of the retention plan "is good 
for our country, because we have reached a good level of prices 
on the world market," and he added El Salvador has only 
approximately 500,000 quintals (22,727 tons) currently retained. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-56184 </DOCNO>
