<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Castro Opens ANPP Session on Economic Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Castro Opens ANPP Session on Economic Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Castro Emphasizes Crisis Solutions </H4>

<F P=102> PA0205011094 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 0004 GMT 2 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0205011094 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Evening Information Review" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Cuban President Fidel Castro said here in Havana 
that the country will have to win its economic battle with 
intelligence, perseverance, and courage, adding that experts and 
politicians alike will have to assume the responsibility that 
this entails by implementing a package of measures to put the 
country's internal finances on a sound basis. 
  During the first day of special sessions at the National 
Assembly of the People's Government, the Cuban leader said that 
the current situation of excess currency was created by a human 
policy adopted by the revolution to leave no one destitute 
during the special period. This, he added, has created an 
excess of money in circulation that is no longer tolerable. It 
must be solved by doing things correctly so the problem does not 
occur again. 
  Fidel Castro said: We have gained the workers' understanding 
after the issue was discussed at the parliaments in the 
workplace, nevertheless, some people do not understand. They 
will only understand when measures follow one another and when 
they are able to fully realize that it is necessary to implement 
them. 
  Jose Luis Rodriguez, finance and prices minister, had 
previously said that the measures must be adopted in an orderly, 
disciplined, gradual manner, adding that it will take up to 18 
months to link one measure with the next. The outlined measures 
include a reduction in the budget deficit, a possible exchange 
[canje] of currency, the freezing of bank accounts for a 
specific time -- offering guarantees to account holders and 
hitting those who have illegally amassed fortunes. Rodriguez 
also expressed the need to strengthen the Cuban peso, to review 
incentives given to priority groups, to increase prices of 
nonessential products and of electricity and telephone rates, 
and to implement a tax policy. 
  Osvaldo Martinez, chairman of the economic commission at the 
National Assembly of the People's Government, agreed with the 
Cuban finance minister but added that, in his opinion, the 
exchange of currency must not be considered only when it is 
appropriate, not as the first and only solution. 
  The special session is being attended by 551 deputies and 
will resume work on Tuesday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

