<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conference To Create Association of Caribbean States </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Conference To Create Association of Caribbean States </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2904225094 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1700 
GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2904225094 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At the First International Conference on the 
Sustainable Development of Small Insular States, which is being 
held in Barbados, a nongovernmental organization proposed that a 
declaration against the U.S. blockade on Cuba be included in the 
conference's final document. The proposal was made by (Peggy 
Antrobus), general coordinator of the Alternative for Women's 
Development, who recognized Cuba's strong emphasis on social 
development and the prioritization of investments in health 
care, education, and social security. 
  As part of that conference, on 4 June, a minisummit will be 
held to create the Association of Caribbean States, which will 
encompass not just English-speaking states but the entire 
Caribbean community, including Cuba. At that meeting, the heads 
of Caribbean states and governments will sign the constitution 
that will govern the association, whose goal is the 
establishment of a solid development program for the whole 
region. 
  Venezuelan Foreign Minister Miguel Angel Burelli Rivas 
underscored the current and historical importance of Caribbean 
union: 
  [Begin Burelli recording] Once again the entire Caribbean 
community is united in a single body and in a single assembly. 
In the last 30 years, despite Cuba's historical and political 
weight, those abroad, specifically European countries, have 
viewed the Caribbean as exclusively English-speaking countries. 
Of course, those countries are very important; but the Caribbean 
includes much more than only those countries. The Caribbean has 
great importance historically, politically, and strategically. 
[end recording] 
  Foreign Minister Burelli added that the Association of 
Caribbean States will have goals identical to those of other 
international organizations, such as the Organization of 
American States. 
  [Begin Burelli recording] Except, in this case, the [words 
indistinct] is official. It will echo all aspects, languages, 
and interests of the Caribbean, which until now have always been 
divided. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

