<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Views Constitutionality Court Ruling </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Views Constitutionality Court Ruling </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3004235294 Guatemala City Teleonce Television in Spanish 
0400 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3004235294 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City Teleonce Television </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Telepress" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Ramiro de Leon Carpio has commented on the 
ruling on the electoral process issued by the Constitutionality 
Court [CC] and on the implications of this ruling for the 
current political situation: 
  [Begin De Leon recording] As for the resolution issued by 
the honorable CC, I said from the very beginning when the amparo 
was filed, that I would respect the independence of the state 
branches. The role of the Executive Branch is over. In a state 
of law in a legal regime, it is absolutely normal for a person, 
institution, or group to adopt the corresponding legal actions 
should he or it disagree with an action, resolution, or law. 
That is how any citizen, such as this deputy, files a recourse. 
  At that time I said that I would respect the ruling issued 
by 
the CC, the top constitutional justice tribunal. That is just 
what I did. At that time I also said -- and this can be 
confirmed today -- that Guatemalans have great trust in one of 
the most credible institutions in Guatemala, the CC. They also 
trust the integrity, and above all, the 
juridical-political-electoral capabilities of the honorable 
magistrates who make up the Supreme Electoral Tribunal. Given 
the experience and knowledge of this organization, the 
population was sure that the call for elections was based on 
legal grounds. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

