<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Candidate Navarro Defends De Greiff's Position </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Candidate Navarro Defends De Greiff's Position </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2904233394 Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in 
Spanish 1200 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2904233394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Antonio Navarro Wolff, </F>
presidential candidate for the Colombian 19 April Movement 
Democratic Alliance, in Santa Fe de Bogota by unidentified 
reporter on 29 April; from the "Caracol's 0600 to 0900" newscast 
-- live or recorded] 
  [Text] [Reporter] We salute Dr. Antonio Navarro Wolff, 
presidential candidate for the 19 April Movement Democratic 
Alliance. Dr. Navarro, what is your opinion of the letter sent 
hours ago by Prosecutor General Gustavo de Greiff to Colombian 
Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin on a diplomatic protest note sent 
by the U.S. Department of State to the Colombian Government 
complaining about the attitude of our nation's top prosecutor? 
Good morning. 
  [Navarro] Good morning. I think the prosecutor general is 
right in his conflict with sectors of the U.S. Government and 
Congress because I think the attitude of placing all the blame 
on us, which was assumed during the Reagan and Bush 
administrations, prevails again in the United States. 
  I think the prosecutor general has complied with legal 
norms; 
he has in no way violated the law. The prosecutor general did 
not draft the Penal Procedure Code; the government and the 
Congress did. Thus, [words indistinct] only enforcing it. 
  I think the prosecutor general has been mistreated. I think 
the summit of governors, which began in Popayan yesterday, 
should defend the dignified and sovereign position assumed by 
the prosecutor general. I do not know whether the government is 
somewhat caught up between [words indistinct] and the need to 
defend its judicial system. What is indeed true, however, is 
that the summit of governors [words indistinct] must support the 
prosecutor general and reject the discriminatory and unfair 
treatment of him by U.S. authorities. 

</TEXT>

