<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Polling Stations Open for Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Polling Stations Open for Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0105133094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1221 GMT 1 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0105133094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Quito, 1 May, (EFE) -- The 15,870 polling stations 
throughout Ecuador opened to voters today at 0700 (1200 GMT) for 
legislative, provincial, and municipal elections, which promise 
few surprises. 
  For several months now, the unanimous prediction has been 
that the opposition Social Christian Party will win. All that 
remains to be seen is the proportion of their victory over Sixto 
Duran-Ballen's conservative government. 
  According to local radio and television stations, election 
day, which concludes at 1700 (2200 GMT), began with no major 
incidents. 
  More than 20,000 candidates from 17 political parties are 
competing for the votes of 6.2 million voters. The people must 
renew 65 of the 77 seats at the single-chamber Congress for a 
two-year term. Also during today's vote, Ecuadoreans will elect 
54 provincial council members and 607 municipal council members 
to a four-year term. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

