<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2904132194 </F>
<F P=103> PY2904132194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Uruguay monitored through 28 
April: 
  The Central Bank of Uruguay reported on 15 April that the 
GDP 
grew 1.5 percent in 1993. The manufacturing industry's 
activities declined by 9 percent; the electricity, gas, and 
water supply companies' activities declined by 4.5 percent; 
agricultural and livestock activities barely grew 0.3 percent; 
fishing activities grew 0.8 percent; construction activities 
grew 13 percent; trade, restaurant, and hotel activities grew 
6.7 percent; and transport and communications activities grew 
9.2 percent. (Montevideo EL PAIS in Spanish 18 Apr 94 Market 
Indicators Section, p 1) 
  Daniel Berti, a National Association of Dairy Farmers board 
member, has announced that milk production increased 11 percent 
since early January. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in 
Spanish 22 Apr 94 Agriculture and Livestock Section, p 1) 
  The Central Bank of Uruguay reported on 21 April that the 
government accumulated a $74-million deficit during the first 
two months of this year. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in 
Spanish 22 Apr 94 p 10) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

