<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Country To Be Used for Repatriation of Taiwanese </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Country To Be Used for Repatriation of Taiwanese </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3004234294 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2356 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA3004234294 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 29 Apr (ACAN-EFE) -- Official 
sources reported today that Guatemala has agreed to lend its 
territory for the repatriation of Taiwan immigrants in response 
to a request from the International Migration Organization 
[Organizacion Internacional para las Migraciones, OIM]. 
  Foreign Minister Maritza Ruiz Vielmann has said that, based 
on a request from the United States and Taiwan, the government 
agreed to do this "as a demonstration of cooperation with the 
OIM," but cautioned that "this decision must not be understood 
as setting a precedent." Vielmann told the media: "The 
cooperation being extended now does not constitute a 
manifestation of a policy in this regard." 
  Guatemala will permit the ship Jinn Yinn I to dock at a 
Guatemalan port. The passengers, who have been traveling in 
very crowded conditions, comprise 102 Chinese [as received] who 
were intercepted without legal documents in waters off 
California by U.S. Coast Guard units. 
  According to Vielmann, President Ramiro De Leon ordered the 
Foreign Relations, Government, and Defense Ministries to form a 
commission to coordinate details for the debarkation and 
"immediate deportation" of the travelers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

