<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Notes `Good' Relations With EU </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Notes `Good' Relations With EU </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0205211994 Panama City Telemetro Television Network in 
Spanish 1730 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0205211994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Telemetro Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Telemetro Reports" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Panama maintains good commercial relations with the 
EU (European Union), although there have been some differences 
regarding some products. This was announced by Commerce and 
Industry Minister Ricardo Fabrega. 
  Although the EU has imposed certain restrictions on our 
country, on products such as bananas, seafood, and fish, 
Commerce and Industry Minister Ricardo Fabrega said multilateral 
commercial relations are at a very high level. A ruling is 
pending in the case of bananas. 
  [Begin Fabrega recording] Within those commercial relations 
we have some differences of opinion, such as on the topic of 
bananas. We have established mechanisms of communication, 
however, and have announced our position. Certain countries of 
the EU support our stand, and this is being defined by a 
tribunal. We expect a ruling will favor our decision sometime 
around October. [end recording] 
  In the case of seafood, Panama will make certain 
modifications so as to later resume commercial relations with 
European countries on this product. 
  [Begin Fabrega recording] In the Athens meeting, we held 
some 
meetings with ranking EU officials. They explained what gave 
rise to the problem with seafood in terms of the rules of origin 
of the seafood. We were able to reach a very satisfactory 
agreement on such rules. We think that within a very short time 
our seafood products will enter the European market duty free. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

