<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Said To Increase Majority in Congress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Said To Increase Majority in Congress </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0205152494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1359 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0205152494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Quito, 2 May (EFE) -- The Ecuadoran opposition 
increased its majority in Congress and dealt a strong blow to 
the conservative government, which only obtained seven of 65 
seats in the legislative elections held on 1 May, according to 
an unofficial vote count of 89.5 percent of the votes revealed 
today. 
  The populist right-wing Social Christian Party (PSC), 
received the most votes, 19 percent, and won 22 seats, according 
to figures provided by the local media (the Supreme Electoral 
Tribunal will only give final results by the end of the month). 
  Second place went to the populist Ecuadoran Roldosist Party 
(PRE), which won 10 seats. Third place went to the Maoist 
Democratic People's Movement (MPD). The social democrat 
Democratic Left Party (ID) won six seats and the Christian 
democrat Popular Democracy Party (DP) won five. 
  President Sixto Duran-Ballen's Republican Unity Party (PUR) 
only obtained two seats, and Vice President Alberto Dahik's 
Conservative Party (PCE) obtained five. According to the Quito 
newspaper EL COMERCIO, there was a high percentage of nullified 
votes (18 percent). 

</TEXT>

