<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Election Campaign Violence Claims 2 Victims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Election Campaign Violence Claims 2 Victims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0205182494 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1733 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0205182494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santo Domingo, 2 May (DPA) -- The violent electoral 
campaign in the Dominican Republic has claimed two more victims, 
who were shot dead yesterday during an incident in which 17 more 
persons were wounded. Those who died were followers of the 
Dominican Revolutionary Party (PRD) who were participating in a 
large caravan that was attacked by unidentified assailants. 
  The dead individuals are Dr. Edgard de la Rosa, 29, and 
Nelson Nunez, 44. It was reported that Nunez was the bodyguard 
of Joaquin Sanchez, who is the PRD candidate for mayor of La 
Vega. 
  The PRD accused the followers of President Joaquin Balaguer 
and of the ruling Social Christian Reformist Party (PRSC) of 
having opened fire on the caravan with heavy-caliber weapons. 
Spokesmen for the opposition party said that since the campaign 
began last 16 March, seven of their followers have been murdered 
in various places and over 100 have been injured. 
  Today, PRD presidential candidate Jose Francisco Pena Gomez 
urged the PRSC and President Balaguer to sign a pact to halt 
violence and "prevent further bloodshed after the 16 May 
elections." Pena Gomez also proposed that none of the parties 
that will participate in the elections declare victory before 
the Central Electoral Board (JCE) makes the official 
announcement. The PRD also asked the Catholic Church to mediate 
so that this pact be signed and "no Dominican fall victim to 
political violence." 
  On 24 April, a 23-year-old woman was shot twice in the head 
and killed when a PRD caravan was attacked in one sector of 
Santo Domingo. Yesterday's incident occurred after the 
conclusion of a PRD regional meeting when a large number of 
followers were returning to La Vega. The shots were apparently 
made with an automatic weapon. The wounded were taken to 
hospitals in La Vega and Santiago. La Vega is some 160 km north 
of Santo Domingo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

